that? Oh, I love autograph sessions. I love it. But it's easy to take it and,
you know, if you were tired or you wanted to be somewhere else, I've never had

00:39.720 --> 00:49.240
the experience of having an endless group of people coming up and demanding my
autograph, you know. I go to autograph sessions that I've been to. We figure if

00:49.240 --> 00:55.160
eight or 12 people come, everybody's very delighted.

00:55.160 --> 00:55.280
it.

00:58.700 --> 01:11.740
I know that some mainstream authors I have read about get very unhappy at
autograph sessions. They get tired. When you read about the American Booksellers

01:11.740 --> 01:19.700
Association Convention, usually they say that the science fiction authors were
among the most agreeable there who just kept signing autographs and signing

01:19.700 --> 01:32.080
autographs and other people got really upset and cranky and so forth and so on.
So it's easy to make up. And we've all had experiences when we were doing

01:32.080 --> 01:42.240
something that we wish we were some slight self. So it's easy to take the
situation and invent it. Whereas as we're sitting there and signing good luck

01:42.240 --> 01:50.780
and best of wishes, et cetera, et cetera, et cetera, and asking them, how do you
spell your name? That I've been through. I've learned that you always ask the

01:50.780 --> 02:00.140
